","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Balderston was born about 1185, in England, United Kingdom. She married Richard de Radcliffe about 1200, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1185–":"umbes 1185–Surnud","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","Abt 1185":"umbes 1185","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","1208":"1208","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1185–":"noin 1185–Kuollut","1182–Male":"1182–Kuollut","1208–Female":"1208–Kuollut","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","Abt 1185":"noin 1185","Abt 1200":"noin 1200","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","1208":"1208","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1185–":"environ 1185–Décédée","1182–Male":"1182–Décédé","1208–Female":"1208–Décédée","1185–Female":"1185–Décédée","Abt 1185":"environ 1185","Abt 1200":"environ 1200","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","1208":"1208","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Ellen Balder